<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="318" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1123,1366]" pageId="1" pageNumber="318">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="318">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Male eyes usually holoptic; interfrontal seta present; proclinate orbital seta usually absent; arista pubescent; mid tibia with 1–3 
<emphasis box="[425,453,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="318">pd</emphasis>
seta; prealar seta well developed; scutellum with two long marginal pairs of setae and a shorter discal pair, and with fine pubescence hairs on ventral surface; proepisternum, meron and anepimeron bare; pregonite small, and with two robust setulae; distiphallus reduced (adapted from 
<bibRefCitation author="Suh, S. J. &amp; Kwon, Y. J." box="[1058,1274,1231,1258]" pageId="1" pageNumber="318" pagination="315 - 317" refId="ref8574" refString="Suh, S. J. &amp; Kwon, Y. J. (2008) A newly recorded species of the genus Botanophila (Insecta: Diptera: Anthomyiidae) in Korea. Korean Journal of systematic Zoology, 24, 315 - 317. https: // doi. org / 10.5635 / KJSZ. 2008.24.3.315" type="journal article" year="2008">Suh &amp; Kwon 2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1123,1366]" pageId="1" pageNumber="318">
An unusual character of the species herein described is the male dichoptic eyes, identical to female (
<figureCitation box="[1337,1432,1267,1293]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,657,681]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,633]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[151,1435,181,633]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Botanophila hernandezi sp. nov. Male: head, frontal view (A); habitus, dorsal view (B); habitus, lateral view (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141821" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141821/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="318">Figs 1A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,188,1303,1329]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,803,827]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,346,779]" captionTargetId="figure-115@4.[151,1435,345,779]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Botanophila mayorgae sp. nov. Male: head, frontal view (A); habitus, dorsal view (B); habitus, lateral view (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141823" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141823/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="318">2A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[201,238,1303,1329]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1907,1931]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,669,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-212@5.[151,1435,669,1884]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Botanophila zaldivari sp. nov. Male: head, frontal view (A); habitus, dorsal view (B); habitus, lateral view (C). Female: head, frontal view (D); habitus, dorsal view (E); habitus, lateral view (F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141825" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141825/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="318">3A</figureCitation>
), whereas the male terminalia is 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lioy" authorityYear="1864" box="[615,753,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Botanophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[615,753,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="318">Botanophila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
- 
<typeStatus box="[761,813,1304,1330]" pageId="1" pageNumber="318">type</typeStatus>
, with pregonite and distiphallus reduced, and the cerci (fused into a cercal plate) long and apically furcated (
<figureCitation box="[749,840,1339,1365]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,951,975]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,561,928]" captionTargetId="figure-239@6.[151,1435,561,928]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Botanophila hernandezi sp. nov. Male terminalia: (A) sternite 5, dorsal view; (B) epandrium, cerci and surstyli, posterior view; (C) epandrium, cerci and surstyli, lateral view; (D) aedeagus and associated structures, lateral view; (E) aedeagus and associated structures, dorsal view. Abbreviations: cerc, cerci; distph, distiphallus; epand, epandrium; phapod, phalapodeme; pgt, postgonite; pregt, pregonite; sur, surstyli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141827" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141827/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="318">Figs 4B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[853,887,1339,1366]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1506,1530]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1107,1481]" captionTargetId="figure-309@6.[151,1435,1107,1482]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Botanophila mayorgae sp. nov. Male terminalia: (A) sternite 5, dorsal view; (B) epandrium, cerci and surstyli, posterior view; (C) epandrium, cerci and surstyli, lateral view; (D) aedeagus and associated structures, lateral view; (E) aedeagus and associated structures, dorsal view. Abbreviations: cerc, cerci; distph, distiphallus; epand, epandrium; epiph, epiphallus; phapod, phalapodeme; pgt, postgonite; pregt, pregonite; sur, surstyli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141829/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="318">5B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[899,936,1339,1366]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1129,1153]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,275,1106]" captionTargetId="figure-61@7.[151,1435,273,1106]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Botanophila zaldivari sp. nov. Male terminalia: (A) sternite 5, dorsal view; (B) epandrium, cerci and surstyli, posterior view; (C) epandrium, cerci and surstyli, lateral view; (D) aedeagus and associated structures, lateral view; (E) aedeagus and associated structures, dorsal view. Female terminalia: (F) ovipositor, dorsal view; (G) ovipositor, ventral view; (H) spermathecae.Abbreviations: cerc, cerci; distph, distiphallus; epand, epandrium; epiph, epiphallus; epipcrt, epiprocto; hypcrt, hypoprocto; phapod, phalapodeme; pgt, postgonite; pregt, pregonite; st, sternite; sur, surstyli; tg, tergite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141831" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141831/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="318">6B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
